## Architecture Standards

### 1. Clean Architecture
- Follow Clean Architecture principles with clear separation of concerns
- Use dependency injection (Hilt) for all dependencies
- Maintain unidirectional data flow
- Keep business logic in domain layer, implementation in data layer

### 2. Package Structure
```
com.dmdbrands.gurus/
├── app/                    # Application layer
├── core/                   # Core utilities, DI, navigation
├── data/                   # Data layer (API, storage, repositories)
├── domain/                 # Domain layer (models, interfaces, services)
└── features/               # Feature modules
```

### 3. Dependency Injection
- Use Hilt for dependency injection
- Provide all dependencies via constructor injection
- Use `@Singleton` for services and repositories
- Use `@ApplicationContext` for context dependencies

---

## Code Style & Documentation

### 1. Kotlin Conventions
- Follow official Kotlin coding conventions
- Use meaningful variable and function names
- Prefer `val` over `var` when possible
- Use expression bodies for simple functions

### 2. Documentation (KDoc)
- Document all public classes, functions, and properties
- Use `@property` for constructor parameters
- Use `@param` for function parameters
- Use `@return` for return values
- Include examples for complex functions

### 3. Naming Conventions
- Use PascalCase for classes, objects, and interfaces
- Use camelCase for variables, functions, and properties
- Use UPPER_SNAKE_CASE for constants
- Prefix interfaces with 'I' (e.g., `IAccountRepository`)

---

## API Best Practices

### 1. Retrofit Interfaces
- Define all API interfaces in `data/api/`
- Use Retrofit annotations (`@GET`, `@POST`, `@PATCH`, `@DELETE`)
- All methods must be `suspend` and return appropriate model types
- Use companion object constants for endpoint paths

### 2. API Documentation
- Document all endpoints with KDoc
- Include parameter descriptions
- Document response types and error cases

### 3. Error Handling
- Use sealed classes for API responses
- Handle network errors gracefully
- Provide meaningful error messages

---

## Data Layer Standards

### 1. DataStore (Proto)
- Use Proto DataStore for structured, type-safe storage
- Define DataStore classes in `data/storage/datastore/`
- Implement serializers for all Proto types
- Use extension properties on Context for DataStore instances

### 2. Room Database
- Define entities in `data/storage/db/entity/`
- Define DAOs in `data/storage/db/dao/`
- Use `@Entity`, `@PrimaryKey`, `@ForeignKey` annotations
- Document all entities and DAO methods

### 3. Repository Pattern
- Define interfaces in `domain/repository/`
- Implement in `data/repository/`
- Use constructor injection for dependencies
- Provide via Dagger Hilt modules

---

## Service Layer Standards

### 1. Service Interfaces
- Define in `domain/services/` or `domain/interfaces/`
- Keep interfaces pure Kotlin (no Android dependencies)
- Use `suspend` or `Flow<T>` for async operations
- Document all methods with KDoc

### 2. Service Implementation
- Implement in `core/service/` or `features/common/service/`
- Use `@Singleton` and `@Inject` annotations
- Inject dependencies via constructor
- Handle errors and provide meaningful logging

### 3. Service Documentation
- Document purpose, parameters, and return values
- Include usage examples for complex services
- Document error handling strategies

---

## Repository Pattern

### 1. Interface Definition
- Define in `domain/repository/`
- Pure Kotlin interfaces (no Android dependencies)
- Use `suspend` or `Flow<T>` for async operations
- Document all methods with KDoc

### 2. Implementation
- Implement in `data/repository/`
- Use `@Singleton` and `@Inject` annotations
- Inject DAOs, DataStores, APIs via constructor
- Override all interface methods

### 3. Dependency Injection
- Provide via Dagger Hilt modules in `core/di/RepositoryModule.kt`
- Use `@Provides` or `@Binds` for binding
- Provide as singletons

---

## Logging Standards

### 1. AppLog Usage
- Use `AppLog` for all production logs
- Use appropriate log levels:
  - `AppLog.i` - General information
  - `AppLog.d` - Debug information
  - `AppLog.w` - Warnings
  - `AppLog.e` - Errors
  - `AppLog.v` - Verbose (development only)
  - `AppLog.a` - Assertions

### 2. Log Structure
- Use descriptive tags (class or feature name)
- Include contextual information
- Structure messages for easy searching
- Avoid logging sensitive data

### 3. Exception Logging
- Always log exceptions with stack traces
- Include relevant context
- Use `AppLog.e` for all exceptions

